Manuscript: Edinburgh NLS Adv. MS. 72.2.2

NLS Adv. MS 72.2.2 comprises fragments of various manuscripts, mostly apparently from the 17th or 18th centuries and some otherwise lost. Through these fragments, bardic poetry inscribed and, in many cases, composed by members of the MacMhuirich family predominates, although numerous other genres are represented to varying extents. One of the largest identified fragments is from NLS Adv. MS 72.1.34, by Eoghan Mac Phail. This also mostly contains poetry.

Hands

Contents

Summary

Four poems are included in this transcription. 1 and 2 are inscribed by Eoghan mac Pháil, 3 by Domhnall Mac Mhuirich, and 4 by Niall Mac Mhuirich: (1) 'Goll mear mileat', a panegyric of Goll mac Morna, Finn mac Cumaill's legendary rival; (2) 'An bfhaca tusa thu fein', a love poem; (3) 'Maith an sgel do sgaoil nar miosg', a praise poem (c. 1696) for Ailin, Chief of Clanranald; (4) 'Domhnall mac raghnuill rosg mall', an anonymous but potentially near-contemporary (so 13th-cent.) panegyric of the eponymous ancestor of Clann Domhnaill. 3 and 4 have been chosen deliberately as specimens of late and early bardic poetry respectively.

Notes

1. The edge of the page runs right along the top of the letters in line 1, meaning some accents or abbreviation markers may have been lost. The most obviously required accents have been supplied. Only visible abbreviations are indicated.

2. This adjective is evidently related to fíad ("game") or fíad ("wild land") but the only available lemma for "fiadhach" means "hunting", which would not fit here syntactically unless one imagine a genitive plural along the clunky lines of "of the huntings" or suchlike.

3. This could be taken as the comparative of solus ("brighter the face of Ó Colla") or the noun, soillse ("sunshine"), in an implied copula construction ("The face of Ó Colla [is] sunshine"). Ther problem with the former is that "dech", in line b, already supplies a comparative.

4. This line is one syllable short; "nglan" is found before "ngorm" in other manuscripts.
